That's right!  The Golgi apparatus forms proacrosomal vesicles, which coalesce to form an acrosomal cap on the nucleus.

Spermiogenesis is a process of cell differentiation in which spermatids, the products of spermatogenesis, become the highly-specialized spermatozoa (sperm), capable of carrying male DNA to the ovum. This is the temperature-sensitive component of sperm production. Sperm remain associated with sustentacular cells throughout this process, and are only released once they are physically mature. The changes that spermatids undergo as they differentiate into sperm is often described in stages:
Golgi phase: the Golgi apparatus forms proacrosomal vesicles, which coalesce to form an acrosomal cap on the nucleus. The centrioles migrate to the opposite end of the nucleus and begin the process of organizing microtubules to form the axoneme of the flagellum, which is similar in structure and function to a cilium.
Cap phase: The acrosomal cap expands to enclose roughly half of the nucleus. The acrosome is a lysosome containing hyaluronidase and a protease called acrosin. When the sperm contacts the ovum, these enzymes are released in a process called the acrosome reaction. They permit the sperm to penetrate the corona radiata and the zona pellucida, in one of the first steps in fertilization.
Acrosome phase: The nucleus is now highly condensed and elongated. It occupies the developing head of the sperm, which remains embedded in the sustentacular cell. The developing tail extends into the lumen of the seminiferous tubule. Mitochondria accumulate around the base of the developing tail, to form the middle piece. They will provide the ATP necessary for flagellar function.
Maturation phase: excess cytoplasm is released as a residual body. Physically mature, but non-motile sperm are released into the testicular fluid of the lumen.
